Here's the complete migration guidance for your `TimedExecutor` class.

## Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern:
- Spawns a thread, joins with timeout, aborts on expiry
- Catches `ThreadAbortException` + calls `ResetAbort()`

In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `ResetAbort()` is a no-op (`SYSLIB0006`).

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload in new code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                             .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If externalToken caused cancellation, OperationCanceledException propagates
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` abandons the task on timeout but the delegate keeps running. If `work` is a tight CPU loop, it burns a thread pool thread until it finishes. Have `work` accept a `CancellationToken` and check it at regular intervals. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking on async code** | The sync overload uses `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` ŌĆö acceptable for migration parity, but prefer the async overload in new call sites. |

## If `work` Can Cooperate (Best Practice)

Refactor callers to pass a `CancellationToken` through:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                         .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example ŌĆö work cooperates by checking the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

This ensures work **actually stops** on timeout rather than being abandoned.

## What Was Removed and Why

| .NET Framework API | Replacement | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` / `CancelAfter` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Not needed ŌĆö check `token.IsCancellationRequested` | No-op / `SYSLIB0006` obsolete |
| Manual `Thread` + `Join` | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` | Uses thread pool; `WaitAsync` provides cancellable waiting |
